{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775871394138,"sessionID":"ses_285d23ea9ffe541yeYBmDfcCbh","part":{"id":"prt_d7a2f0157001ZKtECSDglLM4eK","messageID":"msg_d7a2efae0001lWfW5kEHMFsoXH","sessionID":"ses_285d23ea9ffe541yeYBmDfcCbh","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775871395822,"sessionID":"ses_285d23ea9ffe541yeYBmDfcCbh","part":{"id":"prt_d7a2f0346001OQUO1AX6Yh3Fs0","messageID":"msg_d7a2efae0001lWfW5kEHMFsoXH","sessionID":"ses_285d23ea9ffe541yeYBmDfcCbh","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_4795db5711844d288350606e","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-011: Router JWT Authentication & Issuance\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure router endpoints** - Require valid JWT tokens for accessing backend services through the router\n8: 2. **Enable stateless authentication** - Use JWT's self-contained nature to avoid server-side session lookups for token validation\n9: 3. **Support token issuance** - Provide endpoints for issuing JWT tokens upon successful authentication\n10: 4. **Integrate with existing session management** - Complement the existing session middleware with JWT-based authentication\n11: \n12: ## Scope\n13: \n14: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n15: **Language:** Go  \n16: **Size:** M\n17: \n18: This AR covers:\n19: \n20: - **In scope:**\n21:   - JWT validation middleware for router HTTP handlers\n22:   - JWT issuance endpoint for token generation\n23:   - Configuration for JWT secrets and token expiration\n24:   - Integration with existing session management\n25:   - Unit tests for JWT validation and issuance\n26: \n27: - **Out of scope:**\n28:   - User authentication logic (username/password validation)\n29:   - OAuth2/OIDC integration\n30:   - Token refresh mechanisms\n31:   - RBAC/authorization policies (future AR)\n32: \n33: ## Current State Analysis\n34: \n35: ### Existing Authentication Mechanisms\n36: \n37: The current router implementation has session-based authentication:\n38: \n39: 1. **Session Middleware** (`middleware/session_middleware.go`):\n40:    - Extracts session ID from cookies or headers\n41:    - Validates session against session store (memory/Redis)\n42:    - Attaches session to request context\n43:    - `RequireSession` middleware enforces authentication\n44: \n45: 2. **Session Types** (`session/types.go`):\n46:    - `Session` struct with ID, namespace, kind, backend info\n47:    - Session state management (Active, Idle, Expired, Terminated)\n48:    - Configurable expiration and idle timeouts\n49: \n50: 3. **Session Manager** (`session/manager.go`):\n51:    - CRUD operations for sessions\n52:    - Session cleanup and expiration handling\n53: \n54: ### Issues Identified\n55: \n56: 1. **Stateful authentication** - Every request requires a session store lookup\n57: 2. **No token-based auth** - External clients cannot easily authenticate without session cookies\n58: 3. **Limited scalability** - Session store becomes a bottleneck for distributed deployments\n59: 4. **No standard protocol** - Proprietary session mechanism vs. industry-standard JWT\n60: \n61: ### Kubernetes Client-Go Context\n62: \n63: Per `deployment/client-go.md`, the generated client-go library provides:\n64: - Typed clients for `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources\n65: - Informers for watching resource changes\n66: - Listers for efficient caching\n67: \n68: **Note:** JWT authentication in the router is orthogonal to Kubernetes RBAC. The router operates at the HTTP layer, while Kubernetes RBAC controls access to the API server.\n69: \n70: ## Proposed Changes\n71: \n72: ### 1. JWT Configuration\n73: \n74: Add JWT configuration to `config.go`:\n75: \n76: ```go\n77: type JWTConfig struct {\n78:     // Enabled enables JWT authentication\n79:     Enabled bool `json:\"enabled\"`\n80:     \n81:     // Secret is the JWT signing secret (HMAC) or path to private key (RSA/ECDSA)\n82:     Secret string `json:\"secret\"`\n83:     \n84:     // SecretPath is the path to the JWT secret file\n85:     SecretPath string `json:\"secretPath\"`\n86:     \n87:     // Algorithm is the signing algorithm (HS256, RS256, ES256)\n88:     Algorithm string `json:\"algorithm\"`\n89:     \n90:     // TokenExpiration is the JWT token expiration duration\n91:     TokenExpiration time.Duration `json:\"tokenExpiration\"`\n92:     \n93:     // Issuer is the JWT issuer claim\n94:     Issuer string `json:\"issuer\"`\n95:     \n96:     // Audience is the expected audience claim\n97:     Audience string `json:\"audience\"`\n98: }\n99: \n100: type RouterConfig struct {\n101:     // ... existing fields ...\n102:     JWT JWTConfig `json:\"jwt\"`\n103: }\n104: ```\n105: \n106: ### 2. JWT Claims Structure\n107: \n108: Define custom claims for AgentCube-specific data:\n109: \n110: ```go\n111: type JWTClaims struct {\n112:     jwt.RegisteredClaims\n113:     \n114:     // UserID is the authenticated user's identifier\n115:     UserID string `json:\"userId\"`\n116:     \n117:     // Namespace is the allowed Kubernetes namespace (optional)\n118:     Namespace string `json:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n119:     \n120:     // Roles is the list of assigned roles (for future RBAC)\n121:     Roles []string `json:\"roles,omitempty\"`\n122:     \n123:     // SessionID links to an existing session (optional)\n124:     SessionID string `json:\"sessionId,omitempty\"`\n125: }\n126: ```\n127: \n128: ### 3. JWT Middleware\n129: \n130: Create `middleware/jwt_middleware.go`:\n131: \n132: ```go\n133: type JWTMiddleware struct {\n134:     config *JWTConfig\n135:     key    interface{} // Signing key\n136: }\n137: \n138: func (m *JWTMiddleware) Validate(next http.Handler) http.Handler {\n139:     return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n140:         token, err := m.extractToken(r)\n141:         if err != nil {\n142:             m.writeError(w, \"missing token\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n143:             return\n144:         }\n145:         \n146:         claims, err := m.validateToken(token)\n147:         if err != nil {\n148:             m.writeError(w, \"invalid token\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n149:             return\n150:         }\n151:         \n152:         ctx := context.WithValue(r.Context(), JWTClaimsContextKey, claims)\n153:         r = r.WithContext(ctx)\n154:         next.ServeHTTP(w, r)\n155:     })\n156: }\n157: ```\n158: \n159: ### 4. JWT Issuance Endpoint\n160: \n161: Add token issuance handler in `handler.go`:\n162: \n163: ```go\n164: func (h *Handler) IssueToken(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n165:     // Extract credentials from request\n166:     creds, err := h.extractCredentials(r)\n167:     if err != nil {\n168:         h.writeError(w, \"invalid credentials\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n169:         return\n170:     }\n171:     \n172:     // Validate credentials (delegate to auth provider)\n173:     user, err := h.authProvider.Authenticate(r.Context(), creds)\n174:     if err != nil {\n175:         h.writeError(w, \"authentication failed\", http.StatusUnauthorized)\n176:         return\n177:     }\n178:     \n179:     // Generate JWT\n180:     token, err := h.jwtSigner.Sign(user)\n181:     if err != nil {\n182:         h.writeError(w, \"token generation failed\", http.StatusInternalServerError)\n183:         return\n184:     }\n185:     \n186:     // Return token\n187:     json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(TokenResponse{\n188:         Token:     token,\n189:         ExpiresIn: h.config.JWT.TokenExpiration.Seconds(),\n190:     })\n191: }\n192: ```\n193: \n194: ### 5. Router Integration\n195: \n196: Update `router.go` to optionally enable JWT middleware:\n197: \n198: ```go\n199: func (r *Router) Start(ctx context.Context) error {\n200:     var handler http.Handler = r.handler\n201:     \n202:     if r.config.JWT.Enabled {\n203:         jwtMiddleware := middleware.NewJWTMiddleware(&r.config.JWT)\n204:         handler = jwtMiddleware.Validate(handler)\n205:     }\n206:     \n207:     server := &http.Server{\n208:         Addr:         r.config.ListenAddr,\n209:         Handler:      handler,\n210:         ReadTimeout:  r.config.ReadTimeout,\n211:         WriteTimeout: r.config.WriteTimeout,\n212:         IdleTimeout:  r.config.IdleTimeout,\n213:     }\n214:     \n215:     // ... rest of startup logic ...\n216: }\n217: ```\n218: \n219: ### 6. Token Issuance Route\n220: \n221: Add dedicated route for token issuance (bypasses JWT validation):\n222: \n223: ```go\n224: func (h *Handler) ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n225:     // Token issuance endpoint (no auth required)\n226:     if r.Method == http.MethodPost && r.URL.Path == \"/api/v1/auth/token\" {\n227:         h.IssueToken(w, r)\n228:         return\n229:     }\n230:     \n231:     // All other routes require JWT\n232:     route, err := h.resolver.Resolve(r)\n233:     if err != nil {\n234:         h.writeError(w, err, http.StatusNotFound)\n235:         return\n236:     }\n237:     \n238:     if err := h.ProxyRequest(w, r, route); err != nil {\n239:         h.writeError(w, err, http.StatusBadGateway)\n240:     }\n241: }\n242: ```\n243: \n244: ## Impact Analysis\n245: \n246: ### Files to Create\n247: \n248: | File | Purpose |\n249: |------|---------|\n250: | `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware.go` | JWT validation middleware |\n251: | `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware_test.go` | Middleware unit tests |\n252: | `pkg/router/jwt_signer.go` | JWT signing utilities |\n253: | `pkg/router/jwt_signer_test.go` | Signer unit tests |\n254: \n255: ### Files to Modify\n256: \n257: | File | Changes | Impact |\n258: |------|---------|--------|\n259: | `pkg/router/config.go` | Add `JWTConfig` struct | Low - backward compatible |\n260: | `pkg/router/router.go` | Integrate JWT middleware | Medium - affects request flow |\n261: | `pkg/router/handler.go` | Add token issuance endpoint | Medium - new route |\n262: | `pkg/router/types.go` | Add JWT claims context key | Low - additive |\n263: \n264: ### Dependencies\n265: \n266: Add to `go.mod`:\n267: - `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` - JWT parsing and signing\n268: - Optionally: `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5/request` - Token extraction helpers\n269: \n270: ### Backward Compatibility\n271: \n272: - JWT authentication is **disabled by default** (`JWTConfig.Enabled = false`)\n273: - Existing session-based auth continues to work\n274: - Can run both session and JWT middleware in parallel\n275: \n276: ### Testing Impact\n277: \n278: - Unit tests for JWT signing and validation\n279: - Integration tests for token issuance endpoint\n280: - E2E tests for authenticated routing\n281: - Existing tests unaffected (JWT disabled by default)\n282: \n283: ## Alternatives Considered\n284: \n285: ### Alternative 1: Kubernetes ServiceAccount Tokens\n286: \n287: Use Kubernetes ServiceAccount tokens directly.\n288: \n289: **Pros:**\n290: - No additional token management\n291: - Integrates with Kubernetes RBAC\n292: - Standard for in-cluster communication\n293: \n294: **Cons:**\n295: - Tied to Kubernetes cluster\n296: - Requires API server access for validation\n297: - Overkill for simple router auth\n298: - Limited custom claims\n299: \n300: **Decision:** Defer for future Kubernetes-native integration. JWT provides more flexibility.\n301: \n302: ### Alternative 2: mTLS (Mutual TLS)\n303: \n304: Require client certificates for authentication.\n305: \n306: **Pros:**\n307: - Strong authentication\n308: - No token management\n309: - Encrypted by default\n310: \n311: **Cons:**\n312: - Complex certificate management\n313: - Poor UX for external clients\n314: - Harder to debug\n315: - No fine-grained claims\n316: \n317: **Decision:** Too complex for current requirements. Consider for zero-trust deployments.\n318: \n319: ### Alternative 3: Opaque Bearer Tokens\n320: \n321: Use random opaque tokens with server-side storage.\n322: \n323: **Pros:**\n324: - Simple implementation\n325: - Easy to revoke\n326: - No JWT complexity\n327: \n328: **Cons:**\n329: - Requires token store lookup on every request\n330: - Scalability bottleneck\n331: - More infrastructure to maintain\n332: \n333: **Decision:** JWT's stateless validation is preferable for router performance.\n334: \n335: ### Alternative 4: OAuth2/OIDC\n336: \n337: Integrate with full OAuth2/OIDC provider.\n338: \n339: **Pros:**\n340: - Industry standard\n341: - Rich ecosystem\n342: - Built-in user management\n343: \n344: **Cons:**\n345: - Significant implementation complexity\n346: - Requires OAuth2 server\n347: - Overkill for service-to-service auth\n348: \n349: **Decision:** Defer until user authentication requirements mature.\n350: \n351: ## Implementation Checklist\n352: \n353: - [ ] Add `JWTConfig` to `pkg/router/config.go`\n354: - [ ] Create `pkg/router/middleware/jwt_middleware.go`\n355: - [ ] Create `pkg/router/jwt_signer.go`\n356: - [ ] Add token issuance endpoint to `pkg/router/handler.go`\n357: - [ ] Update `pkg/router/router.go` to integrate JWT middleware\n358: - [ ] Write unit tests for JWT validation\n359: - [ ] Write integration tests for token issuance\n360: - [ ] Update documentation in `deployment/`\n361: - [ ] Add example JWT configuration to manifests\n362: \n363: ## Future Considerations\n364: \n365: 1. **Token Refresh** - Implement refresh token mechanism for long-lived sessions\n366: 2. **RBAC Integration** - Use JWT `roles` claim for authorization decisions\n367: 3. **JWKS Support** - Fetch signing keys from JWKS endpoint for multi-tenant setups\n368: 4. **Token Revocation** - Maintain token blacklist for revocation (Redis-backed)\n369: 5. **OAuth2/OIDC** - Integrate with external identity providers\n370: 6. **ServiceAccount Integration** - Accept Kubernetes ServiceAccount tokens\n371: 7. **Audit Logging** - Log JWT claims for audit trails\n372: \n373: ## References\n374: \n375: - [RFC 7519 - JSON Web Token (JWT)](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7519)\n376: - [github.com/golang-jwt/jwt](https://github.com/golang-jwt/jwt)\n377: - [Kubernetes Authentication](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/authentication/)\n378: - Existing session implementation: `pkg/router/session/`\n379: - Session middleware: `pkg/router/middleware/session_middleware.go`\n\n(End of file - total 379 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-011: Router JWT Authentication & Issuance\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure router endpoints** - Require valid JWT tokens for accessing backend services through the router\n2. **Enable stateless authentication** - Use JWT's self-contained nature to avoid server-side session lookups for token validation\n3. **Support token issuance** - Provide endpoints for issuing JWT tokens upon successful authentication\n4. **Integrate with existing session management** - Complement the existing session middleware with JWT-based authentication\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n\nThis AR covers:\n\n- **In scope:**","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775871395804,"end":1775871395820}}}}
